        <body>
            <div type="edition" subtype="primary" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="grc" resp="#JP" source="https://www.zotero.org/groups/382445/items/Q7KT855P">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1"/><persName type="attested"><name>Βικτωρία</name></persName>
                    <lb n="2"/>χρηστὰ καὶ
                    <lb n="3"/>ἄμεμπτε χαῖ
                    <lb n="4" break="no"/>ρε ἔζησε ἔτη
                    <lb n="5"/><hi rend="supraline">κε</hi>
                    <lb n="6"/><choice><orig>ἷς</orig><reg>εἷς</reg></choice> ἄν τούτῳ ἐπιβου
                    <lb n="7" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">λ</supplied>εύσηται τῷ μνημίῳ <w>δ
                    <lb n="8" break="no"/><choice><orig>ο</orig><reg>ὲ</reg></choice></w> <w><choice><orig>ο</orig><reg>α</reg></choice>ὐτὸν</w> <persName type="divine"><name>Ὅρκος</name></persName>  ἀπο<surplus>ο</surplus>λεῖ </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                    <app><note>Text of Manganaro</note></app>
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation" xml:lang="en" resp="#JP">
                <p>Biktoria, worthy and blameless, lived 25 years. Whoever tampers with this memorial, Horkos will destroy them.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                <p>The first editors assumed that the second part of the text was perhaps written at a different time / by a different hand, but Manganaro assumes the role of a workshop in preparing the 'standard' imprecation below the tablet. In any case, the difference between the larger marble letters and the smaller letters cut onto the limestone base is already sufficient explanation for any difference. Manganaro rightly comments on the selective use of the more precious marble (this practice more familiar from statue bases). The final line is of very uncertain interpretation, appearing to show multiple errors in carving.</p>
            </div>
